        <name>16.2.4.2 T Show convergence</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Examine the convergence of the series \[\sum_{p=1}^\infty a_p= -\dfrac{1}{2!} + \dfrac{1}{4!} - \dfrac{1}{6!} + \dots \]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First, find the general term of the series: &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(a_p=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Write down an expression for the general term of the related series of positive terms:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(|a_p|=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now use the ratio test to examine the convergence of this series:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; \(\dfrac{|a_{p+1}|}{|a_p|}=\) [[input:ans3a]] [[validation:ans3a]], therefore \(\lim_{p \to \infty} \dfrac{|a_{p+1}|}{|a_p|}=\) [[input:ans3b]] [[validation:ans3b]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt3a]] [[feedback:prt3b]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt; Hence the series is [[input:ans4]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt; \[-\dfrac{1}{2!} + \dfrac{1}{4!} - \dfrac{1}{6!} + \dots  = \sum_{p=1}^{\infty} \dfrac{(-1)^p}{(2p)!}\] &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; So \(a_p = \dfrac{(-1)^p}{(2p)!}\) is the general term of the series, and therefore \(|a_p| = \dfrac{1}{(2p)!}\). &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; \[ \begin{aligned} \dfrac{|a_{p+1}|}{|a_p|} &amp;amp; = \dfrac{(2p)!}{(2(p+1)!)} \\ &amp;amp; = \dfrac{2p(2p-1)\dots(2)(1)}{(2p+2)(2p+1)(2p)(2p-1)\dots(2)(1) } \\ &amp;amp; = \dfrac{1}{(2p+2)(2p+1)} \to 0 \quad \mathrm{as} \: p \: \mathrm{increases}\end{aligned}\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; So the series of positive terms is convergent by the ratio test. Hence \(\sum_{p=1}^{\infty} \dfrac{(-1)^p}{(2p)!}\) is absolutely convergent. &lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
